04179nam a22006735i 9780824860158DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20112011hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248601587 a10.1515/97808248601582doi  a(DE-B1597)484408  a(OCoLC)851579544  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0240002bisacsh04a202 .209542221 aBronkhorst, Johannes, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKarma /cJohannes Bronkhorst. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDimensions of Asian Spirituality ;v1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSpecial Topics -- tEditor’s Preface -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Orthodox Karma -- t1. Origins and Religious Use -- t2. Karma in and after Greater Magadha -- t3. Karma in Brahmanism -- t4. Karma and Philosophy -- tPart II. Variants of Karma -- t5. Transfer of Merit -- t6. Competitors of Karma -- t7. From One Life to the Next -- t8. Devotion -- tConcluding Comments -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKarma has become a household word in the modern world, where it is associated with the belief in rebirth determined by one’s deeds in earlier lives. This belief was and is widespread in the Indian subcontinent as is the word “karma” itself. In lucid and accessible prose, this book presents karma in its historical, cultural, and religious context.Initially, karma manifested itself in a number of religious movements—most notably Jainism and Buddhism—and was subsequently absorbed into Brahmanism in spite of opposition until the end of the first millennium C.E. Philosophers of all three traditions were confronted with the challenge of explaining by what process rebirth and karmic retribution take place. Some took the drastic step of accepting the participation of a supreme god who acted as a cosmic accountant, others of opting for radical idealism. The doctrine of karma was confronted with alternative explanations of human destiny, among them the belief in the transfer of merit. It also had to accommodate itself to devotional movements that exerted a major influence on Indian religions.The book concludes with some general reflections on the significance of rebirth and karmic retribution, drawing attention to similarities between early Christian and Indian ascetical practices and philosophical notions that in India draw their inspiration from the doctrine of karma.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aKarma. 0aParapsychology. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aRosemont, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486015840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824860158423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824860158.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK